SUMMARY:POZ Conversations
DESCRIPTION:National Youth HIV/AIDS Awareness Day honors young people's r
 esilience amid HIV disparities\, especially for LGBTQ+ youth and youth of
  color facing stigma and barriers to care.  Join POZ Conversations with B
 ruce E. Smail\, M.A.\, IU LGBTQ+ Culture Center Director and a leader liv
 ing openly with HIV since February 10\, 2003. This conversation will be m
 oderated by Nalini Krishnan\, Interim Program Coordinator. On his site Li
 ving With HIV | Sharing My Story (brucesmail.com)\, Bruce shares raw refl
 ections like: "This morning\, as I was writing… so many emotions resurf
 aced. The first chapter begins with my doctor telling me 'I have some goo
 d news and some bad news.' I felt like I was back in 2003 and reliving th
 is experience again." He shares his story "for those living with HIV\; fo
 r those with family and friends living with HIV\; and for folx to have a 
 better understanding of the day-to-day challenges."  Bruce's leadership s
 hines through three premier HIV/AIDS organizations: Deputy Director of th
 e Black AIDS Institute (nation's leading Black HIV/AIDS policy/advocacy g
 roup)\; Executive Director of The MOCHA Center (leading Black-focused HIV
 /AIDS org in Western NY\, managing $1.1M budget &amp\; expanding testing 
 60%)\; and CEO of Virgin Islands Community AIDS Resource Education (VICAR
 E) (securing $2.45M grants &amp\; launching island-wide testing initiativ
 es). He founded and directed the Indiana University National HIV Conferen
 ce—the first national conference intentionally bridging higher educatio
 n and HIV/AIDS sectors\, attracting 325 participants\, 4 national keynote
 s\, 41 workshops/posters\, and 20 vendors\, positioning IU as a leader in
  health equity. His voice challenges silence as a Black Poz leader.Free s
 ervices on-site: HIV Testing by IU Health Positive Link and STI Testing b
 y Monroe County Health Department. Light refreshments provided.  Question
 s? Email glbtserv@iu.edu (mailto:glbtserv@iu.edu).  All Indiana Universit
 y events\, groups\, activities\, and educational\, cultural\, and histori
 cal observances welcome all IU students and other members of the Indiana 
 University community.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  National Youth HIV/AIDS Awareness Day h
 onors young people's resilience amid HIV disparities\, especially for LGB
 TQ+ youth and youth of color facing stigma and barriers to care.</p><p>  
 Join <strong>POZ Conversations</strong> with <strong>Bruce E. Smail\, M.A
 .</strong>\, IU LGBTQ+ Culture Center Director and a leader living openly
  with HIV since February 10\, 2003. This conversation will be moderated b
 y <strong>Nalini Krishnan</strong>\, Interim Program Coordinator. On his 
 site <em>Living With HIV | Sharing My Story</em> (brucesmail.com)\, Bruce
  shares raw reflections like: "This morning\, as I was writing… so many
  emotions resurfaced. The first chapter begins with my doctor telling me 
 'I have some good news and some bad news.' I felt like I was back in 2003
  and reliving this experience again." He shares his story "for those livi
 ng with HIV\; for those with family and friends living with HIV\; and for
  folx to have a better understanding of the day-to-day challenges."</p><p
 >  Bruce's leadership shines through three premier HIV/AIDS organizations
 : <strong>Deputy Director of the Black AIDS Institute</strong> (nation's 
 leading Black HIV/AIDS policy/advocacy group)\; <strong>Executive Directo
 r of The MOCHA Center</strong> (leading Black-focused HIV/AIDS org in Wes
 tern NY\, managing $1.1M budget &amp\; expanding testing 60%)\; and <stro
 ng>CEO of Virgin Islands Community AIDS Resource Education (VICARE)</stro
 ng> (securing $2.45M grants &amp\; launching island-wide testing initiati
 ves). He founded and directed the <strong>Indiana University National HIV
  Conference</strong>—the first national conference intentionally bridgi
 ng higher education and HIV/AIDS sectors\, attracting 325 participants\, 
 4 national keynotes\, 41 workshops/posters\, and 20 vendors\, positioning
  IU as a leader in health equity. His voice challenges silence as a Black
  Poz leader.</p><p><strong>Free services on-site:</strong> HIV Testing by
  IU Health Positive Link and STI Testing by Monroe County Health Departme
 nt. Light refreshments provided.</p><p>  Questions? Email <a href="mailto
 :glbtserv@iu.edu">glbtserv@iu.edu</a>.</p><p>  All Indiana University eve
 nts\, groups\, activities\, and educational\, cultural\, and historical o
 bservances welcome all IU students and other members of the Indiana Unive
 rsity community.</p>
